article.description: Tamicha Jackson scored a career-high 21 points and Alisa Burras added a season-high 19 points and 10 rebounds as the Portland Fire beat the Houston Comets for the first time in team history, 70-60 Friday night.
article.headline: Fire's ninth win in last 10 most impressive
article.linkText: Fire stay hot with first-ever win over Comets
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Portland Fire got a career game from a
Texan to get their first victory over Houston.

	   Tamicha Jackson scored a career-high 21 points -- 15 in the
second half -- and Alisa Burras added a season-high 19 points and
tied a season high with 10 rebounds as Portland beat the Comets,
70-60 Friday night.

	   "Tonight let us know just how well we are playing,'' said
Jackson, a native of Dallas. "I think I got little more aggressive
than I normally do, as far as going one-on-one.''

	   DeMya Walker scored nine points for the Fire (13-9), who won for
the ninth time in 10 games. It was Portland's first win this year
over one of the top three teams in the Western Conference.

	   "It just feels so good to get this first win against Houston,''
Burras said. "We've been trying for three years to beat this
ballclub. To win at home in front of our fans is just awesome for
our team.''

	   Tina Thompson and Sheryl Swoopes led Houston (16-6) with 22
points each. The Comets have lost three of four after a 10-game
winning streak.

	   Houston held a closed-door team meeting for more than 40 minutes
after the game. Players and coaches were not immediately available
for comment.

	   "We really felt if those two had what we called a soft 20, and
nobody else went crazy on us, that we had enough depth on our team
that we were going to be able to win this game,'' Fire coach Linda
Hargrove said. "It was a great win, it came at a great time, a
time when our team is really coming together and playing really
well.''

	   Houston tied it at 50, but a 9-2 run with about 4 minutes --
sparked by back-to-back hoops by Jackson and a layup and two free
throws by Burras -- left put the Fire up 63-55, and the Comets could
not get closer than six points the rest of the way.

	   "I talked to (Jackson) before the game about how we needed her
to run the team, have her take care of the ball and not take a lot
of chance passes,'' Hargrove said. "I think she played 22 minutes
and didn't have a turnover.''

	   Portland went up by as many as 12 points with about 6 minutes
remaining in the first half. An 8-0 run early in the game and
another 7-0 run midway through the half gave the Fire the lead.

	   But Houston closed the gap, finishing the half on an 18-5 run to
pull within two at 33-31.

	   "When we went in at halftime, we knew that we had to come out
because Houston was going to bring everything they had,'' Burras
said. "It shows that we have grown as a team. We're young, but we
look forward as players to step up to the challenges of a team like
Houston.''

	   Poor shooting hurt the Comets early. After starting 2-for-10,
Houston rallied to finish the half at 43.5 percent. The Fire shot
50 percent.

	   Walker had to leave the game briefly with 8:01 remaining in the
first half. While diving for a loose ball, Walker and Burras hit
heads.

	   In a similar play against Washington on June 28, Walker received
a cracked jaw and had some teeth loosened, forcing her to miss a
game.

	   This time, Walker was able to return after a few minutes on the
bench.
